				<div id="bodyContent">
		            <h3 id="siteSub">From Coursera</h3>
		            <div id="contentSub"></div>
		            		            		            					<!-- start content -->
					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>Definition of <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamification">Gamification</a> on Wikipedia.</p>
<p>Gamification is the ability to apply game elements and game design techniques into non-game context. Essentially thinking outside the box and enabling us to use skills from games in real life situations.</p>
<p>Some major game elements, with descriptions and examples, can be found on <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AgC8f8dxYGaSdG80ZUEwX0pUTHZXU0FJMGJ0Zkl5a0E#gid=0">Google Docs</a>.</p>
<p>A definition of Gamification from WePlay: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://weplay.co/more-than-just-badges-we-plays-definition-of-gamification/">More Than Just Badges: We Playâ€™s Definition of Gamification</a></p>
<p>Gamification is a contested concept. Some say it is a term hijacked by marketers to mean something far more shallow, far less interesting than originally intended, usually something like, "Solve a wide variety of business problems, by encouraging highly valuable user behavior." See e.g.,  <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://plus.google.com/+TimOReilly/posts/TFvQ2FDTKy5">https://plus.google.com/+TimOReilly/posts/TFvQ2FDTKy5</a></p>
<p>The term gamification has three important concepts:
<ol>
<li>Game elements</li>
<li>Game design techniques</li>
<li>Non-game context</li>
</ol></p>

